pes visible on its sides and the dotted indicator on the top. Once seated, the hand moves away, leaving the cube firmly attached and ready.\n\nThe woman uses the camera again. She raises it to her eye, the flashcube on top, and more bright bursts flare from the cube. The flash briefly washes much of the image in white before the cube reappears clear and reflective. After these flashes, a square printed photograph appears against a plain background, bordered in white like an instant or snapshot print. The photo shows a small child in a bathtub with a dog nearby. The child and dog shift through several displayed snapshots: the child turns toward the dog, the dog sits or stands in the bath, and in one photo the child appears to kiss or nuzzle the dog while the dog faces forward. The pictures are presented as captured candid moments, with the white borders taped or framed against a neutral surface.\n\nThe scene changes to a product display. Several Sylvania flashcubes stand upright on and around a package labeled “SYLVANIA FLASH CUBES,” the words arranged in bold block lettering. The cubes are clear and faceted, each showing round reflector-like interiors. More cubes surround the package in the foreground and background, creating the impression of a large supply. The Instamatic camera appears among them, partially nestled into the arrangement, with flashcubes scattered around it. The woman’s face then reappears over the product display in a soft dissolve-like overlap, and she reacts with a surprised look, placing her fingertips over her mouth as if catching herself.\n\nShe turns attention to older-style flash equipment. Holding a regular flash camera beside her face, she displays a camera with a large round metal reflector dish attached above or beside the lens. The reflector is shiny and bowl-shaped, with a small bulb socket at its center. She glances toward it with a knowing side look, then smiles. In her other hand she holds a small round flashbulb between her finger